00:35:43.100 --> 00:35:44.580
get hung up on that job title.

00:35:44.580 --> 00:35:47.780
Again, people have secondary
competencies and passions,

00:35:47.780 --> 00:35:49.750
and they're really
good at other things.

00:35:49.750 --> 00:35:54.660
Let's not limit
their contribution,

00:35:54.660 --> 00:35:57.460
especially in the early
stages of a product,

00:35:57.460 --> 00:35:59.646
during product discovery
and conception.

00:35:59.646 --> 00:36:01.020
Inevitably, people
will fall back

00:36:01.020 --> 00:36:02.260
to their core competencies.

00:36:02.260 --> 00:36:04.426
Engineers will write code
and designers will design.

00:36:04.426 --> 00:36:06.490
But especially in the
early stages of a product,

00:36:06.490 --> 00:36:08.656
let people contribute in
whatever way that they can.

00:36:11.697 --> 00:36:12.530
Other anti-patterns.

00:36:12.530 --> 00:36:13.710
A fear of failure, right?

00:36:13.710 --> 00:36:16.935
My ass is on the line, right?

00:36:16.935 --> 00:36:17.435
Right?

00:36:20.099 --> 00:36:22.390
If I don't get this right,
something's going to happen.

00:36:22.390 --> 00:36:23.180
I'm going to get fired.

00:36:23.180 --> 00:36:24.280
I'm going to get demoted.

00:36:24.280 --> 00:36:26.030
And we create these
cultures, but we never

00:36:26.030 --> 00:36:27.450
consider the scope
of the failure.

00:36:27.450 --> 00:36:29.158
Think about that Amazon
scope of failure.

00:36:29.158 --> 00:36:32.344
If they get 11.6 seconds
worth of a release wrong,

00:36:32.344 --> 00:36:33.010
that's terrific.

00:36:33.010 --> 00:36:34.093
They've learned something.

00:36:34.093 --> 00:36:36.680
And they can roll it back, and
they can move that forward.

00:36:36.680 --> 00:36:40.640
If we take small risks, then
the failure brings learning.

00:36:40.640 --> 00:36:41.940
That's the experimentation.

00:36:41.940 --> 00:36:43.273
And that's what we should value.

00:36:43.273 --> 00:36:45.210
We shouldn't make people
afraid of actually

00:36:45.210 --> 00:36:46.610
getting something wrong.

00:36:46.610 --> 00:36:49.320
That should be, ultimately,
encouraged, right?

00:36:49.320 --> 00:36:51.972
Another is arbitrary deadlines.

00:36:51.972 --> 00:36:53.930
If you owe Paulie money,
you got to pay Paulie.

00:36:53.930 --> 00:36:54.770
Right?

00:36:54.770 --> 00:36:56.250
That's kind of how it works out.

00:36:56.250 --> 00:36:57.840
Arbitrary deadlines
are typically

00:36:57.840 --> 00:36:59.910
just motivational tools.

00:36:59.910 --> 00:37:01.610
There's usually no
real reason to get

00:37:01.610 --> 00:37:03.760
something done by
a certain date.

00:37:03.760 --> 00:37:06.180
And we talked earlier about
what happens when you fix date

00:37:06.180 --> 00:37:07.620
and you fix scope.

00:37:07.620 --> 00:37:09.500
If you fix the
date, that's fine,

00:37:09.500 --> 00:37:11.170
but let the teams
build the best product

00:37:11.170 --> 00:37:14.470
that they can by that
deadline, and then

00:37:14.470 --> 00:37:17.306
let them continue optimizing
it after the deadline passes.

00:37:17.306 --> 00:37:19.680
What ends up happening here,
is the teams end up building

00:37:19.680 --> 00:37:24.877
this CYA culture, where we do
just enough to get things done,

00:37:24.877 --> 00:37:26.960
and then to move things
forward to the next thing.

00:37:26.960 --> 00:37:28.200
We never do our best work.

00:37:28.200 --> 00:37:29.420
We never take risks.

00:37:29.420 --> 00:37:32.010
We never innovate, because
we're afraid that we're not

00:37:32.010 --> 00:37:33.760
going to hit the
deadline, or that we're

00:37:33.760 --> 00:37:36.371
going to get fired,
and so forth.

00:37:36.371 --> 00:37:37.870
And so the things
to think about is,

00:37:37.870 --> 00:37:42.230
how does a culture of
learning change the way

00:37:42.230 --> 00:37:43.069
that a team works?

00:37:43.069 --> 00:37:45.110
Ultimately-- So we talked
about who's on the team

00:37:45.110 --> 00:37:46.990
and how we task the
team, but how do

00:37:46.990 --> 00:37:49.510
we actually get them
to do their best work?

00:37:49.510 --> 00:37:51.593
And there's a couple of
different ways to do this.

00:37:51.593 --> 00:37:53.530
First and foremost,
people take smaller risks.

00:37:53.530 --> 00:37:54.085
Right?

00:37:54.085 --> 00:37:55.500
That's the first tack.

00:37:55.500 --> 00:37:58.700
This could essentially
be the-- you

00:37:58.700 --> 00:38:03.199
could argue this is the MVP
for the GoPro camera, right?

00:38:03.199 --> 00:38:04.240
Let's get that out there.

00:38:04.240 --> 00:38:05.580
Let's try it and
see if it works.

00:38:05.580 --> 00:38:07.270
Let's see what kind of
product we get out of it.

00:38:07.270 --> 00:38:08.936
There's a key principle
in lean thinking

00:38:08.936 --> 00:38:11.690
that says that we're always
moving from doubt to certainty.

00:38:11.690 --> 00:38:14.770
That between us and the
end state of perfection,

00:38:14.770 --> 00:38:17.750
which we never
attain, there's a fog.

00:38:17.750 --> 00:38:21.410
And we can only see two or
three steps into that fog.

00:38:21.410 --> 00:38:24.400
And so to mitigate the risk of
running in the wrong direction,

00:38:24.400 --> 00:38:27.190
we take small steps.

00:38:27.190 --> 00:38:28.130
We take small risks.

00:38:28.130 --> 00:38:29.750
We run experiments.

00:38:29.750 --> 00:38:30.900
We test our hypotheses.

00:38:30.900 --> 00:38:32.810
And if the results
from that experiment

00:38:32.810 --> 00:38:35.130
come back and
confirm our thinking,

00:38:35.130 --> 00:38:37.124
we keep going in that direction.

00:38:37.124 --> 00:38:39.790
But if the results come back and
they say that was the wrong way

00:38:39.790 --> 00:38:44.015
to go, we roll back, or we
pick a different direction.

00:38:44.015 --> 00:38:45.640
Because we don't want
to run head-first

00:38:45.640 --> 00:38:48.700
into the fog assuming that
it's the right way to go.

00:38:48.700 --> 00:38:50.072
We take smaller risks.

00:38:50.072 --> 00:38:50.780
This was awesome.

00:38:50.780 --> 00:38:52.220
I ran into this.

00:38:52.220 --> 00:38:53.130
This is Map My Run.

00:38:53.130 --> 00:38:54.740
You guys know this app?

00:38:54.740 --> 00:38:58.860
I was running in LA this summer
while I was working out there.

00:38:58.860 --> 00:39:01.360
Early in the morning, you can
see the dates, the time stamp,

00:39:01.360 --> 00:39:02.750
so you know I'm not lying.

00:39:02.750 --> 00:39:05.940
6:54 AM I was
already out running.

00:39:05.940 --> 00:39:07.609
And I got to the
end of Venice Pier.

00:39:07.609 --> 00:39:08.650
Venice Pier is beautiful.

00:39:08.650 --> 00:39:11.680
It goes a half mile into the
ocean, and the sun is rising,

00:39:11.680 --> 00:39:14.265
and the palm trees are swaying,
and the surfers are out.

00:39:14.265 --> 00:39:16.265
And so I paused to take
a break and kind of take

00:39:16.265 --> 00:39:17.210
in the scenery.

00:39:17.210 --> 00:39:19.360
And I stopped the
tracking of my run,

00:39:19.360 --> 00:39:22.770
and this beautiful modal
window comes up and says, hey,

00:39:22.770 --> 00:39:26.627
would you like to take photos
and add it to your run?

00:39:26.627 --> 00:39:28.960
And at that moment, I was
feeling particularly inspired.

00:39:28.960 --> 00:39:30.490
Adrenaline's flowing,
and I'm sweating,

00:39:30.490 --> 00:39:31.000
and I'm breathing heavy.

00:39:31.000 --> 00:39:32.030
And I said hell yeah.

00:39:32.030 --> 00:39:34.495
I also liked the fact that
they used the term MVP,

00:39:34.495 --> 00:39:35.620
coming from the lean world.

00:39:35.620 --> 00:39:38.330
They mean most valuable
player, of course.

00:39:38.330 --> 00:39:39.760
But I said, terrific.

00:39:39.760 --> 00:39:40.390
Go MVP.

00:39:40.390 --> 00:39:42.598
And I tap Go MVP, and they're
like, all right, great.

00:39:42.598 --> 00:39:43.550
Give us 30 bucks.

00:39:43.550 --> 00:39:45.170
And you can totally do that.

00:39:45.170 --> 00:39:46.520
And I was, like wah wah.

00:39:46.520 --> 00:39:49.960
No way am I making a rational
purchase decision at 7 o'clock

00:39:49.960 --> 00:39:52.870
in the morning, wheezing, can't
breathe and eyes are burning.

00:39:52.870 --> 00:39:56.500
But, so the end of this workflow
is kind of crappy, right?

00:39:56.500 --> 00:39:59.240
But the beginning--
none of these features

00:39:59.240 --> 00:40:02.330
here ever have to exist.

00:40:02.330 --> 00:40:02.830
Right?

00:40:02.830 --> 00:40:05.470
All you have to do
is put up that modal

00:40:05.470 --> 00:40:09.730
and count the taps on
Go MVP and No Thanks.

00:40:09.730 --> 00:40:11.840
And when you get
enough that say yes,

00:40:11.840 --> 00:40:13.340
I like this-- that's
when you start

00:40:13.340 --> 00:40:15.221
investing in actual
feature development.

00:40:15.221 --> 00:40:15.720
Right?

00:40:15.720 --> 00:40:17.820
That's a small experiment.

00:40:17.820 --> 00:40:19.280
That's a smaller
risk that you can

00:40:19.280 --> 00:40:23.190
take to see if there's any value
in actually investing further

00:40:23.190 --> 00:40:25.020
in building this
particular product.

00:40:25.020 --> 00:40:25.770
Right?

00:40:25.770 --> 00:40:28.860
Because the agile
world has come up

00:40:28.860 --> 00:40:31.890
from an engineering perspective.

00:40:31.890 --> 00:40:36.310
The 17 writers of "The Agile
Manifesto" were engineers.

00:40:36.310 --> 00:40:38.220
And typically agile--
in most organizations

00:40:38.220 --> 00:40:40.720
that I deal with-- comes from
the engineering department.

00:40:40.720 --> 00:40:41.920
It's very rare that
the designers are like,

00:40:41.920 --> 00:40:42.630
let's do agile.

00:40:42.630 --> 00:40:44.620
And the engineers are like,
no, we don't want to do it.

00:40:44.620 --> 00:40:45.580
Let's do waterfall.

00:40:45.580 --> 00:40:47.360
Right?

00:40:47.360 --> 00:40:50.230
What's happened is that we built
these amazing organizations,

00:40:50.230 --> 00:40:52.480
these amazing software
engineering organizations, that

00:40:52.480 --> 00:40:55.200
are incentivized for
the efficient delivery

00:40:55.200 --> 00:40:57.850
of high-quality code.

00:40:57.850 --> 00:41:00.090
But what the agile
process doesn't

00:41:00.090 --> 00:41:03.270
have-- as my friend Bill Scott
likes to say-- is a brain.

00:41:03.270 --> 00:41:06.980
It lacks the capacity to
determine what to build,

00:41:06.980 --> 00:41:09.420
and how to implement it,
and how to design it,

00:41:09.420 --> 00:41:12.260
and what copy to
put on top of it.

00:41:12.260 --> 00:41:15.690
And this experimental,
hypothesis-driven approach,

00:41:15.690 --> 00:41:18.930
where we take small risks
and then we learn from it,

00:41:18.930 --> 00:41:22.540
allows us to drive the
agile process in such a way

00:41:22.540 --> 00:41:25.920
that we get great code and
great design and great copy

00:41:25.920 --> 00:41:27.670
that customers
actually want to use,

00:41:27.670 --> 00:41:29.830
because we've measured
their behavior.

00:41:29.830 --> 00:41:32.040
That's our definition
of success,

00:41:32.040 --> 00:41:34.380
is the change in
customer behavior.

00:41:34.380 --> 00:41:36.790
And we have to remember
that works as designed

00:41:36.790 --> 00:41:39.790
is simply not good
enough anymore.

00:41:39.790 --> 00:41:40.810
So one more.

00:41:40.810 --> 00:41:42.470
I just want to prove to you
how healthy and athletic I am,

00:41:42.470 --> 00:41:44.670
so I'm going to use one
more athletic story here.

00:41:44.670 --> 00:41:46.566
But this is a picture of my gym.

00:41:46.566 --> 00:41:47.440
I live in New Jersey.

00:41:47.440 --> 00:41:48.710
This is a picture of my gym.

00:41:48.710 --> 00:41:52.640
This is my favorite
feature at this gym.

00:41:52.640 --> 00:41:54.910
It's called the cardio
theater, and essentially, it

00:41:54.910 --> 00:41:58.950
is a movie theater with
cardio machines in it.

00:41:58.950 --> 00:41:59.450
That's it.

00:41:59.450 --> 00:42:01.080
So instead of putting your
headphones on and watching

00:42:01.080 --> 00:42:02.882
a movie on a small
screen, you got

00:42:02.882 --> 00:42:04.340
on the elliptical
or the treadmill,

00:42:04.340 --> 00:42:06.970
and they blast the movie
out at you in the morning.

00:42:06.970 --> 00:42:07.470
I like it.

00:42:07.470 --> 00:42:09.290
I love that feature, in fact.

00:42:09.290 --> 00:42:13.340
I usually go in the mornings,
so I arrive around 5:30.

00:42:13.340 --> 00:42:15.632
4:30 in the morning, the
guy comes and opens the gym.

00:42:15.632 --> 00:42:16.590
He turns the lights on.

00:42:16.590 --> 00:42:18.580
He pushes Play on the movie.

00:42:18.580 --> 00:42:20.779
He sees that there's
a picture and he

00:42:20.779 --> 00:42:21.820
hears that there's sound.

00:42:21.820 --> 00:42:25.550
As far as he's concerned,
works as designed.

00:42:25.550 --> 00:42:27.960
And then he goes back
to the front desk.

00:42:27.960 --> 00:42:30.840
I show up at 5:30, along
with half the population

00:42:30.840 --> 00:42:32.270
of northern New Jersey.

00:42:32.270 --> 00:42:34.259
For some reason, everyone's
awake at that hour.

00:42:34.259 --> 00:42:36.800
And as soon as you get more than
two people back here running

00:42:36.800 --> 00:42:41.030
on a treadmill, you can't
hear the movie anymore.

00:42:41.030 --> 00:42:44.247
Unusable, undesirable,
works as designed.

00:42:44.247 --> 00:42:45.830
I have to get off
the treadmill and go

00:42:45.830 --> 00:42:48.990
to the front every single day,
and tell the guy to turn it up

00:42:48.990 --> 00:42:50.821
because we can't hear the movie.

00:42:50.821 --> 00:42:53.070
So we have to ensure that
just because a feature works

00:42:53.070 --> 00:42:57.470
as designed, people actually
want to use it and can use it.

00:42:57.470 --> 00:43:00.149
And the way we do that is with
clear definition of success.

00:43:00.149 --> 00:43:02.190
Can we change customer
behavior in the right way?

00:43:02.190 --> 00:43:05.590
And we can measure that.

00:43:05.590 --> 00:43:08.100
And we use that as the mile
marker for whether or not

00:43:08.100 --> 00:43:09.630
we're building the right things.

00:43:09.630 --> 00:43:13.140
Now again, we want to promote
competencies over roles.

00:43:13.140 --> 00:43:16.010
We want people to do whatever
it is that they're good at

00:43:16.010 --> 00:43:17.790
to help us move forward faster.

00:43:17.790 --> 00:43:19.670
And then lastly and
most importantly,

00:43:19.670 --> 00:43:21.845
we want to promote
team self organization.

00:43:21.845 --> 00:43:23.470
Give teams a little
structure, and then

00:43:23.470 --> 00:43:26.606
let them figure out how
best to work together,

00:43:26.606 --> 00:43:28.480
and how best to achieve
the goals that you've

00:43:28.480 --> 00:43:30.050
set out for them.

00:43:30.050 --> 00:43:31.770
This is a quote from
Geoff Nicholson,

00:43:31.770 --> 00:43:33.340
who invented the Post-It note.

00:43:33.340 --> 00:43:36.290
He said that 3M wanted to
productize this thing with Six

00:43:36.290 --> 00:43:38.360
Sigma as soon as he
had thought of it.

00:43:38.360 --> 00:43:40.340
And he had no proof
that customers actually

00:43:40.340 --> 00:43:42.240
wanted this thing yet.

00:43:42.240 --> 00:43:44.620
We don't want to impose
a process on the team

00:43:44.620 --> 00:43:47.880
just because we think it's
good for the production of code

00:43:47.880 --> 00:43:49.130
or the production of features.

00:43:49.130 --> 00:43:49.630
Right?

00:43:49.630 --> 00:43:52.810
Let the teams figure out
exactly what they need to build,

00:43:52.810 --> 00:43:57.770
and when they need to scale it,
and how best to work together.

00:43:57.770 --> 00:43:59.700
Last thing I want to say.

00:43:59.700 --> 00:44:01.117
This is hard work.

00:44:01.117 --> 00:44:03.575
All of this, everything I just
told you to do is difficult.

00:44:03.575 --> 00:44:04.910
It's process change.

00:44:04.910 --> 00:44:06.040
It's culture change.

00:44:06.040 --> 00:44:07.920
Why should you do it?

00:44:07.920 --> 00:44:08.420
Why?

00:44:08.420 --> 00:44:09.570
Why invest in it?

00:44:09.570 --> 00:44:11.450
If things are going
OK, why do it?

00:44:11.450 --> 00:44:14.530
First and foremost, you're going
to make your customers happy,

00:44:14.530 --> 00:44:17.662
or you're going to build stuff
they actually want and can use,

00:44:17.662 --> 00:44:19.370
which means they'll
come back and use it,

00:44:19.370 --> 00:44:21.578
and they'll tell their
friends, and they'll share it,

00:44:21.578 --> 00:44:23.800
and you'll have more customers.

00:44:23.800 --> 00:44:26.920
You'll reduce waste by building
more successful products

00:44:26.920 --> 00:44:30.020
and not working for a
long time on products that

00:44:30.020 --> 00:44:32.390
don't stand a chance of success.

00:44:32.390 --> 00:44:36.750
We'll focus our people and
our time more effectively.

00:44:36.750 --> 00:44:39.499
And then lastly, this
increases employee morale.

00:44:39.499 --> 00:44:41.790
It allows people to feel like
they're part of a greater

00:44:41.790 --> 00:44:45.480
whole, there's a bigger
mission, their ideas count.

00:44:45.480 --> 00:44:46.292
They're loyal.

00:44:46.292 --> 00:44:47.750
They're passionate
about the ideas,

00:44:47.750 --> 00:44:49.583
because they are
ultimately their ideas that

00:44:49.583 --> 00:44:51.110
solve these problems.

00:44:51.110 --> 00:44:53.050
And that's terrific
for your hiring brand

00:44:53.050 --> 00:44:55.250
and for your
retention over time.

00:44:55.250 --> 00:44:57.630
At the end of day, let
me leave you with this.

00:44:57.630 --> 00:45:01.620
You have to transform from
a culture of delivery,

00:45:01.620 --> 00:45:03.400
focused on getting
features out the door,

00:45:03.400 --> 00:45:05.914
to a culture of learning.

00:45:05.914 --> 00:45:07.330
Thank you very
much for listening.

00:45:07.330 --> 00:45:09.334
I'd love to take your questions.

00:45:09.334 --> 00:45:15.010
[APPLAUSE]

00:45:15.010 --> 00:45:15.520
Questions.

00:45:15.520 --> 00:45:16.811
I know we have mics over there.

00:45:16.811 --> 00:45:17.505
Yes, sir.

00:45:17.505 --> 00:45:19.630
AUDIENCE: You give some
great examples of companies

00:45:19.630 --> 00:45:21.919
that do this, they iterate fast.

00:45:21.919 --> 00:45:22.710
They learn quickly.

00:45:22.710 --> 00:45:25.540
They try a lot of experiments,
like Amazon, Facebook,

00:45:25.540 --> 00:45:26.527
even Google.

00:45:26.527 --> 00:45:28.860
But there's a company that
writes a lot of software that

00:45:28.860 --> 00:45:30.950
doesn't seem to do
this, and that's Apple.

00:45:30.950 --> 00:45:33.340
Nevertheless, they've
been very successful.

00:45:33.340 --> 00:45:37.520
So can you explain why
they managed to get things

00:45:37.520 --> 00:45:40.540
right without seeming to try all
of these constant experiments?

00:45:40.540 --> 00:45:42.750
JEFF GOTHELF: I would argue
that they do experiment,

00:45:42.750 --> 00:45:45.470
and that they certainly do a
significant amount of research.

00:45:45.470 --> 00:45:47.460
I just don't think that
we see a lot of it.

00:45:47.460 --> 00:45:52.629
And I don't think that-- they're
certainly not public with it

00:45:52.629 --> 00:45:54.920
like the rest of the companies
that you just mentioned,

00:45:54.920 --> 00:45:57.460
like Google and
Facebook, and so forth.

00:45:57.460 --> 00:46:01.770
I think what Apple really excels
at is understanding ecosystems.

00:46:01.770 --> 00:46:04.280
And they do this by
observation and by research

00:46:04.280 --> 00:46:06.000
and by learning.

00:46:06.000 --> 00:46:11.940
And then when they come,
they take ambitious gambles

00:46:11.940 --> 00:46:14.550
at design-driven innovation
to solve the problems

00:46:14.550 --> 00:46:16.959
that they're viewing
in these ecosystems.

00:46:16.959 --> 00:46:18.750
Now you could say look,
hey, you know what?

00:46:18.750 --> 00:46:21.204
They don't test, and they
don't talk to customers.

00:46:21.204 --> 00:46:22.620
I think they do
talk to customers,

00:46:22.620 --> 00:46:24.900
and I think they absolutely
build prototypes and run

00:46:24.900 --> 00:46:25.470
experiments.

00:46:25.470 --> 00:46:28.650
They seem to lose them in bars
in Palo Alto fairly regularly,

00:46:28.650 --> 00:46:29.150
right?

00:46:29.150 --> 00:46:31.592
But also take a look
at the iteration

00:46:31.592 --> 00:46:33.550
after iteration after
iteration of the hardware

00:46:33.550 --> 00:46:35.780
and the software products
that you're using for them,

00:46:35.780 --> 00:46:37.700
and you can see that
those essentially

00:46:37.700 --> 00:46:39.690
end up being experiments.

00:46:39.690 --> 00:46:45.700
I mean the original iPhone
feels like a rock compared

00:46:45.700 --> 00:46:47.840
to an iPhone 6 these days.

00:46:47.840 --> 00:46:50.930
And I think that there's
experimentation and tons

00:46:50.930 --> 00:46:52.770
of learning there.

00:46:52.770 --> 00:46:55.760
Incidentally, so I
think that's one thing.

00:46:55.760 --> 00:46:57.990
Related is there's a
Chinese company called

00:46:57.990 --> 00:47:01.300
[? Chaomi ?] that
manufactures cellphone,

00:47:01.300 --> 00:47:02.426
mobile phones, and tablets.

00:47:02.426 --> 00:47:03.716
And they're competing directly.

00:47:03.716 --> 00:47:05.650
They're trying to compete
with Apple, anyway.

00:47:05.650 --> 00:47:08.570
They do iterative
design on their hardware

00:47:08.570 --> 00:47:12.000
and their software in one-week
iterations, which is amazing.

00:47:12.000 --> 00:47:14.800
Every Tuesday they
ship 100,000 phones.

00:47:14.800 --> 00:47:17.710
People snap them up, and they're
on the phone with these people,

00:47:17.710 --> 00:47:19.590
and they're measuring
usage to understand

00:47:19.590 --> 00:47:21.750
how well the products
are meeting their needs.

00:47:21.750 --> 00:47:24.176
And so that's what I've
seen as evidence of that.

00:47:24.176 --> 00:47:25.800
Now the last thing
I'll say about this,

00:47:25.800 --> 00:47:27.633
because this question
comes up all the time,

00:47:27.633 --> 00:47:31.230
is you can't dismiss some
level of design genius.

00:47:31.230 --> 00:47:32.920
Right?

00:47:32.920 --> 00:47:36.709
You have to give some credit
to Steve Jobs and the very few

00:47:36.709 --> 00:47:38.250
people in the world
who are like him,

00:47:38.250 --> 00:47:41.520
like Jony Ive and so forth,
who have this design genius.

00:47:41.520 --> 00:47:43.450
I don't think you
can dismiss that

00:47:43.450 --> 00:47:46.910
as part of the component
of their success.

00:47:46.910 --> 00:47:49.220
But I think the design
genius, the creativity,

00:47:49.220 --> 00:47:52.390
comes in in solving
real problems.

00:47:52.390 --> 00:47:54.640
And they see those real
problems by observation

00:47:54.640 --> 00:47:56.630
and understanding ecosystems.

00:47:56.630 --> 00:47:57.550
That's what I think.

00:47:57.550 --> 00:47:59.337
Yeah?

00:47:59.337 --> 00:48:00.920
AUDIENCE: I was
wondering if you could

00:48:00.920 --> 00:48:03.700
talk a little bit about the
structuring of small teams

00:48:03.700 --> 00:48:07.470
in big organizations
such as here,

00:48:07.470 --> 00:48:11.700
where there are literally
hundreds of engineers and tens

00:48:11.700 --> 00:48:15.110
of product managers,
just in one product.

00:48:15.110 --> 00:48:17.820
So do you see these teams
forming and reforming?

00:48:17.820 --> 00:48:21.587
Do you see these teams have
cross product, cross function?

00:48:21.587 --> 00:48:22.920
So how do you imagine them work?

00:48:22.920 --> 00:48:26.882
And then related to that, what
is the decision-making process

00:48:26.882 --> 00:48:27.840
like in that structure?

00:48:27.840 --> 00:48:30.180
JEFF GOTHELF: Yeah, it's a
great, really great questions.

00:48:30.180 --> 00:48:31.570
I don't claim to
have all the answers.

00:48:31.570 --> 00:48:34.153
I can share with you a couple
of anecdotes from my experience,

00:48:34.153 --> 00:48:37.880
and something interesting that
I heard last week on my travels.

00:48:37.880 --> 00:48:42.530
So the team structure itself,
typically designer, product

00:48:42.530 --> 00:48:45.550
manager, and engineers, so
like, one, one, and then two

00:48:45.550 --> 00:48:49.550
to four engineers as far
as each one of those pods.

00:48:49.550 --> 00:48:52.540
And I think you'll see that
repeated in some of the other,

00:48:52.540 --> 00:48:55.700
like the Spotify
whitepaper that was out.

00:48:55.700 --> 00:48:58.650
I think what's interesting
is if you've got-- so

00:48:58.650 --> 00:49:01.825
taking the-- if you've
got a big problem

00:49:01.825 --> 00:49:03.950
and you've got a set of
engineers or a set of teams

00:49:03.950 --> 00:49:07.050
that are working towards
solving this particular problem,

00:49:07.050 --> 00:49:09.320
I think you give that
problem to all those teams.

00:49:09.320 --> 00:49:11.700
And I heard Mary Poppendieck
speak last night.

00:49:11.700 --> 00:49:14.390
Mary Poppendieck is-- she's
one of the legends of the Agile

00:49:14.390 --> 00:49:14.890
world.

00:49:14.890 --> 00:49:17.140
She's been around
35, 40 years, trying

00:49:17.140 --> 00:49:19.050
to make this stuff work
in large companies.

00:49:19.050 --> 00:49:25.810
And she was talking about
giving these pods, essentially,

00:49:25.810 --> 00:49:28.190
all the same problem,
and incentivizing them

00:49:28.190 --> 00:49:31.270
the same way, so everyone
has the same incentives

00:49:31.270 --> 00:49:33.530
to achieve the same
success criteria.

00:49:33.530 --> 00:49:36.812
And then they have to build
dependencies on each other.

00:49:36.812 --> 00:49:38.270
They have to work
together in order

00:49:38.270 --> 00:49:41.690
to achieve that
overarching goal.

00:49:41.690 --> 00:49:43.600
So that's one way to
kind of unite them

00:49:43.600 --> 00:49:45.474
in a similar direction.

00:49:45.474 --> 00:49:46.890
I think the question
then becomes,

00:49:46.890 --> 00:49:48.740
how do you make decisions?

00:49:48.740 --> 00:49:51.360
I've seen it work
one of two ways.

00:49:51.360 --> 00:49:53.140
And again, that's
just my experience.

00:49:53.140 --> 00:49:54.840
It's not necessarily the answer.

00:49:54.840 --> 00:49:58.710
Either there is a product lead,
typically a product manager.

00:49:58.710 --> 00:50:00.710
Although it could be
the design leader.

00:50:00.710 --> 00:50:03.309
There's a team lead
who makes a decision.

00:50:03.309 --> 00:50:05.600
And where I've seen it work,
actually, more effectively

00:50:05.600 --> 00:50:07.770
is that there's a triumvirate
of the product lead,

00:50:07.770 --> 00:50:10.710
the tech lead, and
the design lead, who

00:50:10.710 --> 00:50:12.650
kind of gather all these
ideas from the team,

00:50:12.650 --> 00:50:15.112
and then make a decision
together, and then

00:50:15.112 --> 00:50:16.320
bring that back to the teams.

00:50:16.320 --> 00:50:18.860
I've seen that work well, also.

00:50:18.860 --> 00:50:19.370
Yes, sir?

00:50:19.370 --> 00:50:21.850
AUDIENCE: I'm Interested
in constraints, things

00:50:21.850 --> 00:50:25.570
like legal or regulatory
or just bureaucratic,

00:50:25.570 --> 00:50:27.010
and where they live.

00:50:27.010 --> 00:50:28.930
So these teams
are generally kind

00:50:28.930 --> 00:50:31.100
of constraints on
innovation, as well,

00:50:31.100 --> 00:50:33.760
or least boundaries
of innovation.

00:50:33.760 --> 00:50:37.060
Should the team itself
own that constraint

00:50:37.060 --> 00:50:39.710
and possibly be
demoralized by it?

00:50:39.710 --> 00:50:41.355
Or should it be
external, in which case

00:50:41.355 --> 00:50:45.940
it becomes kind of an enemy
or a systematic problem?

00:50:45.940 --> 00:50:48.430
JEFF GOTHELF: I think you have
to work within your reality,

00:50:48.430 --> 00:50:48.930
right?

00:50:48.930 --> 00:50:51.180
So if you work in
health care, there

00:50:51.180 --> 00:50:52.620
are going to be
legal constraints

00:50:52.620 --> 00:50:54.420
and personal
information constraints,

00:50:54.420 --> 00:50:56.640
privacy constraints, that
you have to work with,

00:50:56.640 --> 00:50:58.990
and same thing in financial
services and so forth.

00:50:58.990 --> 00:51:01.750
I don't think that
you can ignore them.

00:51:01.750 --> 00:51:04.120
And I think you risk damage.

00:51:04.120 --> 00:51:05.510
Forget legal damage
for a second,

00:51:05.510 --> 00:51:07.770
but I think you
risk brand damage

00:51:07.770 --> 00:51:10.385
if you choose to flaunt those
in favor of experimentation

00:51:10.385 --> 00:51:11.195
and hypothesis.

00:51:11.195 --> 00:51:17.040
Now that being said, the
rigidity of those constraints

00:51:17.040 --> 00:51:21.010
is debatable in
certain situations,

00:51:21.010 --> 00:51:25.510
and I think that if you can
have a realistic conversation

00:51:25.510 --> 00:51:28.450
with legal department,
for example,

00:51:28.450 --> 00:51:31.210
or the branding
department, or IT,

00:51:31.210 --> 00:51:33.260
or whoever is
constraining your ability

00:51:33.260 --> 00:51:36.110
to learn the things
that you need to learn,

00:51:36.110 --> 00:51:37.690
I'm confident that
you can typically

00:51:37.690 --> 00:51:40.229
find ways to get around that.

00:51:40.229 --> 00:51:41.270
I'll give you an example.

00:51:41.270 --> 00:51:44.050
We did a lot of experimentation
with a big financial services

00:51:44.050 --> 00:51:46.680
company downtown from here.

00:51:46.680 --> 00:51:51.470
Again, 100-year-old brand, lots
of financial data-- it's risky.

00:51:51.470 --> 00:51:55.780
Options are-- you can test
off-brand, for example,

00:51:55.780 --> 00:51:57.940
so it has nothing to do
with the official brand.

00:51:57.940 --> 00:51:59.000
That's one test.

00:51:59.000 --> 00:52:01.807
You can opt people into
a beta-tester pool.

00:52:01.807 --> 00:52:03.390
So you're self-selecting
a little bit.

00:52:03.390 --> 00:52:04.390
There's some bias there.

00:52:04.390 --> 00:52:07.020
You get the more tech-savvy
individuals, and so forth.

00:52:07.020 --> 00:52:10.920
But at least they've agreed to
take part in these experiments.

00:52:10.920 --> 00:52:13.640
But there are ways to get around
this where you can negotiate

00:52:13.640 --> 00:52:15.140
with the people who
are constraining

00:52:15.140 --> 00:52:17.650
you to get some
kind of learning.

00:52:17.650 --> 00:52:19.910
I think that you
have to own it, and I

00:52:19.910 --> 00:52:22.451
don't think you can disregard
it, because ultimately whatever

00:52:22.451 --> 00:52:24.690
you come up with has to
live in that world as well.

00:52:24.690 --> 00:52:26.231
And I think that if
you disregard it,

00:52:26.231 --> 00:52:29.520
you're building something that's
probably destined to fail.

00:52:29.520 --> 00:52:30.289
Yes, sir.

00:52:30.289 --> 00:52:32.580
AUDIENCE: I also have a
question about the small teams.

00:52:32.580 --> 00:52:35.390
So the first question
is, what's the best way,

00:52:35.390 --> 00:52:37.080
in your experience,
to incentivize

00:52:37.080 --> 00:52:39.320
people to do their best
within the small teams?

00:52:39.320 --> 00:52:42.160
And second question is, when
you have the small teams,

00:52:42.160 --> 00:52:44.690
and you want to encourage them
to kind of all collaborate

00:52:44.690 --> 00:52:47.350
and work together on something,
but then in that environment,

00:52:47.350 --> 00:52:48.990
how do you assign
credit correctly

00:52:48.990 --> 00:52:51.599
so that people, again, have
incentives to kind of--

00:52:51.599 --> 00:52:53.640
JEFF GOTHELF: Well, you
assume that taking credit

00:52:53.640 --> 00:52:54.530
is incentive.

00:52:54.530 --> 00:52:56.510
And I suppose that
that could be.

00:52:56.510 --> 00:52:59.060
The way-- so again,
based on my experience,

00:52:59.060 --> 00:53:01.960
the way that I've seen
the best incentive

00:53:01.960 --> 00:53:05.400
has been to let people
figure out the solution.

00:53:05.400 --> 00:53:07.920
There's an amazing
level-- there's

00:53:07.920 --> 00:53:11.300
an exponentially bigger level
of passion and commitment

00:53:11.300 --> 00:53:14.870
to the success of an
initiative if the team

00:53:14.870 --> 00:53:18.290
is working on an idea
they came up with.

00:53:18.290 --> 00:53:21.570
The difference between telling
a team to build something

00:53:21.570 --> 00:53:24.020
and telling them to figure
out how to solve this problem

00:53:24.020 --> 00:53:25.640
is the incentive.

00:53:25.640 --> 00:53:27.111
That's what gets
them to motivate.

00:53:27.111 --> 00:53:28.610
That's what gets
them moved forward.

00:53:28.610 --> 00:53:32.590
And the interesting thing--
if you buy my concept

00:53:32.590 --> 00:53:37.150
that the atomic object of
innovation is the team,

00:53:37.150 --> 00:53:39.727
then the team wins together
or the team loses together.

00:53:39.727 --> 00:53:41.310
There's no, the team
did great design,

00:53:41.310 --> 00:53:42.700
but the engineers messed it up.

00:53:42.700 --> 00:53:43.200
Right?

00:53:43.200 --> 00:53:44.020
There's none of that.

00:53:44.020 --> 00:53:44.770
It doesn't happen.

00:53:44.770 --> 00:53:46.100
The product is the product.

00:53:46.100 --> 00:53:49.670
You can't separate great
engineering from great design.

00:53:49.670 --> 00:53:53.260
And we managed to
achieve our business

00:53:53.260 --> 00:53:54.941
goal and the
customer's need, and it

00:53:54.941 --> 00:53:56.190
seems to be a winning product.

00:53:56.190 --> 00:53:58.740
That to me has been the
greatest source of incentive

00:53:58.740 --> 00:54:01.892
to get these teams to
work well together.

00:54:01.892 --> 00:54:03.047
OK?

00:54:03.047 --> 00:54:03.630
Anything else?

